{
  "answer": "**In Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, the heaviest *saqi*-couplet—richest in intimate imagery and direct address amid despair—appears in ghazal 198:**[^1]\n\n> O Saqi, pour from your cupped hands, if you must hate;  \n> If not the cup, at least grant wine to seal my fate.\n\nHere, beyond mere pouring, the *saqi* is beseeched to serve personally from cupped hands (an erotic, disdainful intimacy rejecting the goblet), even in hatred, to deliver fatal wine and end the lover's torment.[^2]\n\n**In Allama Iqbal's *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, the weightiest *saqi*-couplet—most prophetic and era-defining—comes in poem 5:**[^3]\n\n> Gone is that age, O Cupbearer, of drinking in the dark of night,  \n> The world becomes one tavern, and each soul will be a drunken wight.\n\nBeyond pouring, the *saqi* (as mystic vintner) is invoked to usher in a unveiled epoch: secret, shadowed imbibing ends; the cosmos turns public tavern, compelling universal ecstasy.[^4]\n\nIqbal's *saqi* evolves further in *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* (ch. 25), wielding \"new\" grace (*lutf*) and wrath (*sitam*), but the Part 2 address packs heaviest revelatory punch.[^5]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 198 [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/198-woh-aa-ke-khwaab-mein-taskeen-e-iztiraab-to-de/translation/#p-02279c).\n[^2]: Ibid.\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 5 [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/05-zamana-aaya-hai-be-hijabi-ka-aam-deedaar-e-yaar-ho/translation/#p-445c2f).\n[^4]: Ibid.\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 25 [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/25-wataniyat/translation/#p-79b1e9).",
